<subSubSection pageId="44" pageNumber="549" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1127,1012,1581]" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,268,1012,1036]" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Body smaller (males 11.18–12.26 mm, females 11.39–12.47 mm). Antennomere 1 short, much shorter than both antennomere 2 and length of pronotum. Sexual dimorphism not expressed. Callar lobe distinctly gibbose in both sexes (
<figureCitation box="[787,912,1076,1100]" captionStart="Figs 60–63. 60–61" captionStartId="48.[151,188,1540,1559]" captionTargetBox="[211,1066,225,1498]" captionTargetId="figure-10@48.[205,1073,219,1507]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="Figs 60–63. 60–61 – Physopelta (Physopeltoides) dentipes sp. nov. 60 – male, paratype; 61 – female, paratype.62–63 – Physopelta (Afrophysopelta) melanoptera Distant, 1904. 62 – male; 63 – female. (Photo: L. Dembický)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739997" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739997/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Figs 60–61</figureCitation>
). Profemora of both sexes strongly incrassate (
<figureCitation box="[431,514,1108,1132]" captionStart="Figs 48–51" captionStartId="46.[151,188,927,946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,904]" captionTargetId="figure-10@46.[151,1126,219,905]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figs 48–51. Physopelta (Physopeltoides) dentipes sp. nov., male, paratype. 48 – fore coxae and trochanters (magnification 60×), 49 – detail of procoxa and protrochanter (90×), 50 – fore leg, anterior view (35×), 51 – ventral surface of profemur (40×). Scale bars: 0.5 mm. (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739993" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739993/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Figs 51</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[526,595,1108,1132]" captionStart="Figs 60–63. 60–61" captionStartId="48.[151,188,1540,1559]" captionTargetBox="[211,1066,225,1498]" captionTargetId="figure-10@48.[205,1073,219,1507]" captionTargetPageId="48" captionText="Figs 60–63. 60–61 – Physopelta (Physopeltoides) dentipes sp. nov. 60 – male, paratype; 61 – female, paratype.62–63 – Physopelta (Afrophysopelta) melanoptera Distant, 1904. 62 – male; 63 – female. (Photo: L. Dembický)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739997" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739997/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">60–61</figureCitation>
), ventral surface with longitudinal furrow, row of small denticles on each side of furrow, and two larger teeth anteapically on dorsal surface (
<figureCitation box="[159,283,1172,1196]" captionStart="Figs 48–51" captionStartId="46.[151,188,927,946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,904]" captionTargetId="figure-10@46.[151,1126,219,905]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figs 48–51. Physopelta (Physopeltoides) dentipes sp. nov., male, paratype. 48 – fore coxae and trochanters (magnification 60×), 49 – detail of procoxa and protrochanter (90×), 50 – fore leg, anterior view (35×), 51 – ventral surface of profemur (40×). Scale bars: 0.5 mm. (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739993" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739993/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Figs 50–51</figureCitation>
). Tibiae ventrally unarmed in both sexes. Ventral sides of meso- and metafemora with small denticles along their entire length. Stridulatory organs lacking, procoxa ventrally without tubercle (
<figureCitation box="[336,460,1236,1261]" captionStart="Figs 48–51" captionStartId="46.[151,188,927,946]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,219,904]" captionTargetId="figure-10@46.[151,1126,219,905]" captionTargetPageId="46" captionText="Figs 48–51. Physopelta (Physopeltoides) dentipes sp. nov., male, paratype. 48 – fore coxae and trochanters (magnification 60×), 49 – detail of procoxa and protrochanter (90×), 50 – fore leg, anterior view (35×), 51 – ventral surface of profemur (40×). Scale bars: 0.5 mm. (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739993" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739993/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Figs 48–49</figureCitation>
). Peritreme of metathoracic scent gland oriented longitudinally, crescent-shaped, projecting both anteriad and posteriad of ostiole (as on 
<figureCitation box="[892,1012,1268,1292]" captionStart="Figs 64–69" captionStartId="56.[150,187,1274,1293]" captionTargetBox="[151,1126,220,1256]" captionTargetId="figure-10@56.[151,1128,219,1256]" captionTargetPageId="56" captionText="Figs 64–69. Physopelta (Afrophysopelta) melanoptera Distant, 1904, male. 64 – fore coxae and trochanters (magnification 75×); 65 – detail of procoxa and protrochanter (110×); 66–67 – profemur: 66 – anterior view (35×), 67 – ventral surface (70×); 68 – external scent efferent system (100×); 69 – peritreme and evaporatorium (170×). Scale bars: 0.2 mm (Figs 64, 66–68), 0.5 mm (Figs 65, 69). (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5740001" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5740001/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Figs 68–69</figureCitation>
). Paramere with apex short and narrow, outer margin basally with small angulate process (
<figureCitation box="[990,1114,1300,1324]" captionStart="Figs 52–59" captionStartId="47.[113,149,1514,1533]" captionTargetBox="[113,1088,219,1433]" captionTargetId="figure-12@47.[113,1088,219,1433]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="Figs 52–59.Physopelta (Physopeltoides) dentipes sp.nov., male.52–54 – pygophore:52 – dorsal view (magnification 75×), 53 – postero-dorsal view (75×), 54 – lateral view (70×). 55–59 – paramere (different orientations; 230×).Scale bars: 0.2 mm. (SEM micrographs: P. Kment)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5739995" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5739995/files/figure.png" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Figs 55–59</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="44.[151,1127,1012,1581]" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,401,1332,1356]" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Stehlík, 2013" authorityName="Stehlík" authorityYear="2013" box="[406,567,1334,1357]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Physopeltoides">
<emphasis box="[406,567,1334,1357]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Physopeltoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[574,708,1332,1356]" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ahmad &amp; Abbas" authorityYear="1987" box="[757,916,1334,1357]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Neophysopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[757,916,1334,1357]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Neophysopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
share the following characters, suggesting a possible sister relationship of both taxa: i) antennomere 1 shorter than antennomere 2; ii) profemora incrassate; iii) meso- and metafemora ventrally with longitudinal furrow of small denticles. However, in 
<taxonomicName authority="Stehlík, 2013" authorityName="Stehlík" authorityYear="2013" box="[564,725,1430,1453]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Physopeltoides">
<emphasis box="[564,725,1430,1453]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Physopeltoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[731,865,1428,1452]" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
the characters ii) and iii) occur in both sexes, whereas in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Ahmad &amp; Abbas" authorityYear="1987" box="[487,646,1462,1485]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Neophysopelta" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[487,646,1462,1485]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Neophysopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
these are developed only in males. 
<taxonomicName authority="Stehlík, 2013" authorityName="Stehlík" authorityYear="2013" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Afrophysopelta">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Afrophysopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[224,358,1492,1516]" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName authority="Stehlík, 2013" authorityName="Stehlík" authorityYear="2013" box="[497,658,1494,1517]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Physopeltoides">
<emphasis box="[497,658,1494,1517]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Physopeltoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[664,799,1492,1516]" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
In its profemora not incrassate and meso- and metafemora ventrally unarmed. On the other hand, 
<taxonomicName authority="Stehlík, 2013" authorityName="Stehlík" authorityYear="2013" box="[874,1036,1526,1549]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Afrophysopelta">
<emphasis box="[874,1036,1526,1549]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Afrophysopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel pageId="44" pageNumber="549" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Stehlík, 2013" authorityName="Stehlík" authorityYear="2013" box="[248,409,1558,1581]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" status="subgen. nov." subGenus="Physopeltoides">
<emphasis box="[248,409,1558,1581]" italics="true" pageId="44" pageNumber="549">Physopeltoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[416,551,1556,1580]" pageId="44" pageNumber="549" rank="subGenus">subgen. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
share the same shape of peritreme and paramere.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="45" pageNumber="550" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="45.[113,1088,220,276]" pageId="45" pageNumber="550">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[113,240,220,244]" pageId="45" pageNumber="550">Etymology.</emphasis>
The name of the subgenus is derived from the nominotypical subgenus 
<taxonomicName box="[972,1088,221,244]" class="Insecta" family="Largidae" genus="Physopelta" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="45" pageNumber="550" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[972,1088,221,244]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="550">Physopelta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
using the Greek suffix - 
<emphasis box="[365,421,253,276]" italics="true" pageId="45" pageNumber="550">oides</emphasis>
, meaning ‘resembling, similar to; the gender is masculine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
